04490nam a22007095i 9781477309230DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212016txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015033635  a97814773092307 a10.7560/3092232doi  a(DE-B1597)587676  a(OCoLC)1269268745  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aF2659.N4bF375 2016 4aF2659.N4bF375 2016 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a305.896/0812231 aFarfán-Santos, Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBlack Bodies, Black Rights :bThe Politics of Quilombolismo in Contemporary Brazil /cElizabeth Farfán-Santos. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (196 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface La Negra Tomasa -- tAcknowledgments -- tAcronyms -- tIntroduction A “Problematic” Field -- tChapter One. Black Heroes: Rewriting Black Resistance and Quilombo History -- tChapter Two. Black Identities: Conceiving Blackness and Quilombolismo -- tChapter Three. Black Lives: “We Are Quilombolas!” -- tChapter Four. Black Rights: Documentation, Proof, and Authenticity -- tChapter Five. Black Justice: Grande Paraguaçu and the Growing Fight for Quilombola Justice -- tConclusion -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUnder a provision in the Brazilian constitution, rural black communities identified as the modern descendants of quilombos—runaway slave communities—are promised land rights as a form of reparations for the historic exclusion of blacks from land ownership. The quilombo provision has been hailed as a success for black rights; however, rights for quilombolas are highly controversial and, in many cases, have led to violent land conflicts. Although thousands of rural black communities have been legally recognized, only a handful have received the rights they were promised. Conflict over quilombola rights is widespread and carries important consequences for race relations and political representations of blackness in twenty-first century Brazil. Drawing on a year of field research in a quilombola community, Elizabeth Farfán-Santos explores how quilombo recognition has significantly affected the everyday lives of those who experience the often-complicated political process. Questions of identity, race, and entitlement play out against a community’s struggle to prove its historical authenticity—and to gain the land and rights they need to survive. This work not only demonstrates the lived experience of a new, particular form of blackness in Brazil, but also shows how blackness is being mobilized and reimagined to gain social rights and political recognition. Black Bodies, Black Rights thus represents an important contribution to the rapidly growing interdisciplinary field of Afro-Latino studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aBlacksxCivil rightszBrazil. 0aBlacksxPolitical activityzBrazil. 0aBlacksxRace identityzBrazil. 0aBlackszBrazilxSocial conditions. 0aBlackszBrazil. 0aQuilomboszBrazil. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/30922340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477309230423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477309230/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK